 What Recession? https://ritholtz.com/2023/06/what-recession/Barry Ritholtz Mon, 26 Jun 2023 13:30:57 +0000 Data AnalysisMacro/Econ https://ritholtz.com/?p=315425 <p> Rising rates, falling savings, increased deficits, dubious GDP: Ever since the yield curve inverted and warnings of “imminent recession” filled the air, the Philly Fed&#39;s map of State Coincident Indexes has provided a good real-time snapshot of the state of the economy. Friday&#39;s release might have snuck by, but its filled with upside surprises that…</p><p> <a class="button" href="https://ritholtz.com/2023/06/what-recession/">Read More<i class="icon ion-arrow-right-c"></i></a></p><p> The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://ritholtz.com/2023/06/what-recession/">What Recession?</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://ritholtz.com">The Big Picture</a> .</p> ; <p> <a href="https://ritholtz.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/State-Coinc-May-2023-2.png" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" class="alignnone wp-image-315429" src="https://ritholtz.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/State-Coinc-May-2023-2.png" alt="" width="720" height="581" srcset="https://ritholtz.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/State-Coinc-May-2023-2.png 1486w, https://ritholtz.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/State-Coinc-May-2023-2-300x242.png 300w, https://ritholtz.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/State-Coinc-May-2023-2-1024x827.png 1024w, https://ritholtz.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/State-Coinc-May-2023-2-768x620.png 768w, https://ritholtz.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/State-Coinc-May-2023-2-250x202.png 250w" sizes="(max-width: 720px) 100vw, 720px" /></a></p><p></p><p> <em>Rising rates, falling savings, increased deficits, dubious GDP</em> : Ever since the yield curve inverted and warnings of “imminent recession” filled the air, the Philly Fed&#39;s map of <a href="https://ritholtz.com/?s=State+Coincident+Indexes" target="_blank" rel="noopener">State Coincident Indexes</a> has provided a good real-time snapshot of the state of the economy. Friday&#39;s release might have snuck by, but its filled with upside surprises that are worth looking at.</p><p> The overview is simple: Over the past 3 months, the coincident indexes for all 50 states indexes have increased (Diffusion index = 100). Last month (May 2023), indexes increased in 47 of 50 states, were flat in 2 states (Minnesota and Rhode Island), and fell in just 1 (Wisconsin). Other states that were softish include New Jersey, Arkansas, and Kentucky.</p><p> Ned Davis Research crunches the state coincident indexes into a probability chart that shows but a 1% chance we are currently in a recession. This is not a prediction, but rather, a reading of the coincident indexes as a current recession indicator.</p><p> <strong>NDR Recession Probability Model: 1% chance of a recession currently</strong><br /> <a href="https://ritholtz.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/ndr-rec-1.jpg" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" class="alignnone wp-image-315470" src="https://ritholtz.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/ndr-rec-1.jpg" alt="" width="720" height="488" srcset="https://ritholtz.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/ndr-rec-1.jpg 982w, https://ritholtz.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/ndr-rec-1-300x203.jpg 300w, https://ritholtz.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/ndr-rec-1-768x520.jpg 768w, https://ritholtz.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/ndr-rec-1-250x169.jpg 250w" sizes="(max-width: 720px) 100vw, 720px" /></a><br /> NDR via<a href="https://twitter.com/RyanDetrick/status/1673094052609241094" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Ryan Detrick</a></p><p> <span style="text-decoration: underline;"><br />Side note</span> : The yield curve has been inverted for what feels like forever. Note that the <a href="https://fred.stlouisfed.org/graph/?g=16sgK" target="_blank" rel="noopener">10 Year minus the 3-Month</a> Treasuries — the recession forecast indicator created by <a href="https://www.fuqua.duke.edu/faculty/campbell-harvey" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Duke Fuqua school of business</a> professor <a href="https://ritholtz.com/2021/09/mib-campbell-harvey-on-defi/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Harvey Campbell</a> inverted in 2019, then again briefly in 2020, then went deep once the FOMC began raising rates in 2022:</p><p> <a href="https://ritholtz.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/10-Year-T-Minus-3-Month-ann.png" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" class="alignnone wp-image-315478" src="https://ritholtz.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/10-Year-T-Minus-3-Month-ann.png" alt="" width="720" height="246" srcset="https://ritholtz.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/10-Year-T-Minus-3-Month-ann.png 1318w, https://ritholtz.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/10-Year-T-Minus-3-Month-ann-300x102.png 300w, https://ritholtz.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/10-Year-T-Minus-3-Month-ann-1024x350.png 1024w, https://ritholtz.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/10-Year-T-Minus-3-Month-ann-768x262.png 768w, https://ritholtz.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/10-Year-T-Minus-3-Month-ann-250x85.png 250w" sizes="(max-width: 720px) 100vw, 720px" /></a></p><p></p><p> Despite its near-perfect history of recession forecasting, perhaps the yield curve inversion is less prophetic when coming off of a decade of Fed Funds at zero. Regardless, it is extremely difficult to objectively look at the current data and state we are in a recession currently or will be anytime soon.</p><p> The wildcard? How much the FOMC overtightens rates and causes a recession through their too fast/too many/too high future rate hikes…</p><p></p><p></p><p> <em>Previously</em> :<br /> <a href="https://ritholtz.com/2022/06/recession-no/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Are We in a Recession? (No)</a> (June 1, 2022)</p><p> <a href="https://ritholtz.com/2022/09/data-nber-recession/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">What Data Makes NBER Recession Calls?</a> (September 1, 2022)</p><p> <a href="https://ritholtz.com/2022/01/the-post-normal-economy/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">The Post-Normal Economy</a> (January 7, 2022)</p><p> <a href="https://ritholtz.com/2023/05/10-bad-takes-on-this-market/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">10 Bad Takes On This Market</a> (May 19, 2023)</p><p></p><p> <em>Sources</em> :<br /> <a href="https://www.philadelphiafed.org/surveys-and-data/regional-economic-analysis/state-coincident-indexes" target="_blank" rel="noopener">State Coincident Indexes Current Report</a> ( <a href="https://www.philadelphiafed.org/-/media/frbp/assets/surveys-and-data/coincident/2023/coincidentindexes0523.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener">PDF</a> )<br /> Federal Reserve Bank of Philadelphia, May 2023</p><p></p><p> The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://ritholtz.com/2023/06/what-recession/">What Recession?</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://ritholtz.com">The Big Picture</a> .</p> ;
